":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1â†’---\\n     2â†’name: agent-integration\\n     3â†’description: >\\n     4â†’  Run all three agent integration phases sequentially: research, write-tests,\\n     5â†’  and implement using E2E-first TDD (unit tests written last).\\n     6â†’  For individual phases, use /agent-integration:research,\\n     7â†’  /agent-integration:write-tests, or /agent-integration:implement.\\n     8â†’  Use when the user says \\\"integrate agent\\\", \\\"add agent support\\\", or wants\\n     9â†’  to run the full agent integration pipeline end-to-end.\\n    10â†’---\\n    11â†’\\n    12â†’# Agent Integration â€” Full Pipeline\\n    13â†’\\n    14â†’Run all three phases of agent integration in a single session. Parameters are collected once and reused across all phases.\\n    15â†’\\n    16â†’## Parameters\\n    17â†’\\n    18â†’Collect these before starting (ask the user if not provided):\\n    19â†’\\n    20â†’| Parameter | Description | How to derive |\\n    21â†’|-----------|-------------|---------------|\\n    22â†’| `AGENT_NAME` | Human-readable name (e.g., \\\"Gemini CLI\\\") | User provides |\\n    23â†’| `AGENT_PACKAGE` | Go package dir name â€” **no hyphens** | Lowercase, remove hyphens/spaces |\\n    24â†’| `AGENT_KEY` | Registry key for `agent.Register()` and `entire enable` | Check existing patterns in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/registry.go` |\\n    25â†’| `AGENT_BIN` | CLI binary name | `command -v <binary>` |\\n    26â†’| `LIVE_COMMAND` | Full command to launch agent | User provides |\\n    27â†’| `EVENTS_OR_UNKNOWN` | Known hook event names, or \\\"unknown\\\" | From agent docs or \\\"unknown\\\" |\\n    28â†’\\n    29â†’**Note:** These identifiers can differ. Run `grep -r 'AgentName\\\\|func.*Name()' cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/` and `e2e/agents/` to see how existing agents handle the split.\\n    30â†’\\n    31â†’## Architecture References\\n    32â†’\\n    33â†’These documents define the agent integration contract:\\n    34â†’\\n    35â†’- **Implementation guide**: `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` â€” Step-by-step code templates, event mapping, testing patterns\\n    36â†’- **Integration checklist**: `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` â€” Design principles and validation criteria\\n    37â†’\\n    38â†’## Scope\\n    39â†’\\n    40â†’This skill targets **hook-capable agents** â€” those that support lifecycle hooks\\n    41â†’(implementing `HookSupport` from `agent.go`). Agents that use file-based detection\\n    42â†’(implementing `FileWatcher`) require a different integration approach not covered here.\\n    43â†’Check `agent.go` for the current interface definitions.\\n    44â†’\\n    45â†’## Core Rule: E2E-First TDD\\n    46â†’\\n    47â†’This skill enforces strict E2E-first test-driven development. The rules:\\n    48â†’\\n    49â†’1. **E2E tests are the spec.** The existing `ForEachAgent` test scenarios define what \\\"working\\\" means. The agent runner makes those tests runnable for the new agent.\\n    50â†’2. **Run E2E tests at every step.** Each implementation tier starts by running the E2E test and watching it fail. You implement until it passes. No exceptions.\\n    51â†’3. **Unit tests are written last.** After all E2E tiers pass (Step 14), you write unit tests using real data collected from E2E runs as golden fixtures.\\n    52â†’4. **If you didn't watch it fail, you don't know if it tests the right thing.** Never write a test you haven't seen fail first.\\n    53â†’5. **Minimum viable fix.** At each E2E failure, implement only the code needed to fix that failure. Don't anticipate future tiers.\\n    54â†’6. **`/debug-e2e` is your debugger.** When an E2E test fails, use the artifact directory with `/debug-e2e` before guessing at fixes.\\n    55â†’\\n    56â†’## Pipeline\\n    57â†’\\n    58â†’Run these three phases in order. Each phase builds on the previous phase's output.\\n    59â†’\\n    60â†’### Phase 1: Research\\n    61â†’\\n    62â†’Discover the agent's hook mechanism, transcript format, and configuration through binary probing and documentation research. Produces an implementation one-pager at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/AGENT.md` that the other phases use as their single source of agent-specific information.\\n    63â†’\\n    64â†’Read and follow the research procedure from `.claude/skills/agent-integration/researcher.md`.\\n    65â†’\\n    66â†’**Expected output:** Implementation one-pager at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/AGENT.md` and a test script at `scripts/test-$AGENT_SLUG-agent-integration.sh`.\\n    67â†’\\n    68â†’**Commit:** After the research phase completes, use `/commit` to commit all files.\\n    69â†’\\n    70â†’**Gate:** If the verdict is INCOMPATIBLE, stop and discuss with the user before proceeding.\\n    71â†’\\n    72â†’### Phase 2: Write E2E Runner\\n    73â†’\\n    74â†’Create the E2E agent runner so existing test scenarios can exercise the new agent. No unit tests are written in this phase â€” no new test scenarios either (existing `ForEachAgent` tests are the spec).\\n    75â†’\\n    76â†’Read and follow the procedure from `.claude/skills/agent-integration/test-writer.md`.\\n    77â†’\\n    78â†’**Expected output:** E2E agent runner at `e2e/agents/$AGENT_SLUG.go` that compiles and registers with the test framework.\\n    79â†’\\n    80â†’**Commit:** After the E2E runner compiles and registers, use `/commit` to commit all files.\\n    81â†’\\n    82â†’### Phase 3: Implement (E2E-First, Unit Tests Last)\\n    83â†’\\n    84â†’Build the Go agent package using strict E2E-first TDD. E2E tests drive development at every step â€” run each tier, watch it fail, implement the minimum fix, repeat. Unit tests are written only after all E2E tiers pass, using real data from E2E runs as golden fixtures.\\n    85â†’\\n    86â†’Read and follow the implement procedure from `.claude/skills/agent-integration/implementer.md`.\\n    87â†’\\n    88â†’**Expected output:** Complete agent package at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/` with all E2E tiers passing and unit tests locking in behavior.\\n    89â†’\\n    90â†’**Note:** `AGENT.md` is a living document â€” Phases 2 and 3 update it when they discover new information during testing or implementation.\\n    91â†’\\n    92â†’## Final Validation\\n    93â†’\\n    94â†’After all three phases, run the complete validation:\\n    95â†’\\n    96â†’```bash\\n    97â†’mise run fmt      # Format\\n    98â†’mise run lint     # Lint\\n    99â†’mise run test:ci  # All tests (unit + integration)\\n   100â†’```\\n   101â†’\\n   102â†’Summarize:\\n   103â†’- Compatibility verdict from Phase 1\\n   104â†’- Files created in Phases 2 and 3\\n   105â†’- Test coverage\\n   106â†’- Any remaining TODOs or gaps\\n   107â†’\"}]},\"uuid\":\"c44fb88c-59ff-45e8-9969-8cd367e63919\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-28T00:31:18.446Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot/.claude/skills/agent-integration/SKILL.md\",\"content\":\"---\\nname: agent-integration\\ndescription: >\\n  Run all three agent integration phases sequentially: research, write-tests,\\n  and implement using E2E-first TDD (unit tests written last).\\n  For individual phases, use /agent-integration:research,\\n  /agent-integration:write-tests, or /agent-integration:implement.\\n  Use when the user says \\\"integrate agent\\\", \\\"add agent support\\\", or wants\\n  to run the full agent integration pipeline end-to-end.\\n---\\n\\n# Agent Integration â€” Full Pipeline\\n\\nRun all three phases of agent integration in a single session. Parameters are collected once and reused across all phases.\\n\\n## Parameters\\n\\nCollect these before starting (ask the user if not provided):\\n\\n| Parameter | Description | How to derive |\\n|-----------|-------------|---------------|\\n| `AGENT_NAME` | Human-readable name (e.g., \\\"Gemini CLI\\\") | User provides |\\n| `AGENT_PACKAGE` | Go package dir name â€” **no hyphens** | Lowercase, remove hyphens/spaces |\\n| `AGENT_KEY` | Registry key for `agent.Register()` and `entire enable` | Check existing patterns in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/registry.go` |\\n| `AGENT_BIN` | CLI binary name | `command -v <binary>` |\\n| `LIVE_COMMAND` | Full command to launch agent | User provides |\\n| `EVENTS_OR_UNKNOWN` | Known hook event names, or \\\"unknown\\\" | From agent docs or \\\"unknown\\\" |\\n\\n**Note:** These identifiers can differ. Run `grep -r 'AgentName\\\\|func.*Name()' cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/` and `e2e/agents/` to see how existing agents handle the split.\\n\\n## Architecture References\\n\\nThese documents define the agent integration contract:\\n\\n- **Implementation guide**: `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` â€” Step-by-step code templates, event mapping, testing patterns\\n- **Integration checklist**: `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` â€” Design principles and validation criteria\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nThis skill targets **hook-capable agents** â€” those that support lifecycle hooks\\n(implementing `HookSupport` from `agent.go`). Agents that use file-based detection\\n(implementing `FileWatcher`) require a different integration approach not covered here.\\nCheck `agent.go` for the current interface definitions.\\n\\n## Core Rule: E2E-First TDD\\n\\nThis skill enforces strict E2E-first test-driven development. The rules:\\n\\n1. **E2E tests are the spec.** The existing `ForEachAgent` test scenarios define what \\\"working\\\" means. The agent runner makes those tests runnable for the new agent.\\n2. **Run E2E tests at every step.** Each implementation tier starts by running the E2E test and watching it fail. You implement until it passes. No exceptions.\\n3. **Unit tests are written last.** After all E2E tiers pass (Step 14), you write unit tests using real data collected from E2E runs as golden fixtures.\\n4. **If you didn't watch it fail, you don't know if it tests the right thing.** Never write a test you haven't seen fail first.\\n5. **Minimum viable fix.** At each E2E failure, implement only the code needed to fix that failure. Don't anticipate future tiers.\\n6. **`/debug-e2e` is your debugger.** When an E2E test fails, use the artifact directory with `/debug-e2e` before guessing at fixes.\\n\\n## Pipeline\\n\\nRun these three phases in order. Each phase builds on the previous phase's output.\\n\\n### Phase 1: Research\\n\\nDiscover the agent's hook mechanism, transcript format, and configuration through binary probing and documentation research. Produces an implementation one-pager at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/AGENT.md` that the other phases use as their single source of agent-specific information.\\n\\nRead and follow the research procedure from `.claude/skills/agent-integration/researcher.md`.\\n\\n**Expected output:** Implementation one-pager at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/AGENT.md` and a test script at `scripts/test-$AGENT_SLUG-agent-integration.sh`.\\n\\n**Commit:** After the research phase completes, use `/commit` to commit all files.\\n\\n**Gate:** If the verdict is INCOMPATIBLE, stop and discuss with the user before proceeding.\\n\\n### Phase 2: Write E2E Runner\\n\\nCreate the E2E agent runner so existing test scenarios can exercise the new agent. No unit tests are written in this phase â€” no new test scenarios either (existing `ForEachAgent` tests are the spec).\\n\\nRead and follow the procedure from `.claude/skills/agent-integration/test-writer.md`.\\n\\n**Expected output:** E2E agent runner at `e2e/agents/$AGENT_SLUG.go` that compiles and registers with the test framework.\\n\\n**Commit:** After the E2E runner compiles and registers, use `/commit` to commit all files.\\n\\n### Phase 3: Implement (E2E-First, Unit Tests Last)\\n\\nBuild the Go agent package using strict E2E-first TDD. E2E tests drive development at every step â€” run each tier, watch it fail, implement the minimum fix, repeat. Unit tests are written only after all E2E tiers pass, using real data from E2E runs as golden fixtures.\\n\\nRead and follow the implement procedure from `.claude/skills/agent-integration/implementer.md`.\\n\\n**Expected output:** Complete agent package at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/` with all E2E tiers passing and unit tests locking in behavior.\\n\\n**Note:** `AGENT.md` is a living document â€” Phases 2 and 3 update it when they discover new information during testing or implementation.\\n\\n## Final Validation\\n\\nAfter all three phases, run the complete validation:\\n\\n```bash\\nmise run fmt      # Format\\nmise run lint     # Lint\\nmise run test:ci  # All tests (unit + integration)\\n```\\n\\nSummarize:\\n- Compatibility verdict from Phase 1\\n- Files created in Phases 2 and 3\\n- Test coverage\\n- Any remaining TODOs or gaps\\n\",\"numLines\":107,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":107}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"fe18b4ec-e734-4e73-a1bb-a131537d25fb\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"c44fb88c-59ff-45e8-9969-8cd367e63919\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"a97d7bdc-76ad-4774-b13f-b81bdd064352\",\"version\":\"2.1.62\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/improve-agent-integration-skill\",\"slug\":\"vast-purring-aurora\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01JZ1TCpmiEGRfma1hK5YmRy\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_015BFG28f8ePaSC5x2RXFisa\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot/.claude/skills/agent-integration/test-writer.md\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":\"tool_use\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":19350,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":23111,\"output_tokens\":262,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":19350,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYZXMQfo3SK4hdoTux42B\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"f23f9109-6815-41aa-a287-e66a3615ca83\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-28T00:31:18.899Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"f23f9109-6815-41aa-a287-e66a3615ca83\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"a97d7bdc-76ad-4774-b13f-b81bdd064352\",\"version\":\"2.1.62\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/improve-agent-integration-skill\",\"slug\":\"vast-purring-aurora\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Read\",\"command\":\"callback\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_015BFG28f8ePaSC5x2RXFisa\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_015BFG28f8ePaSC5x2RXFisa\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-28T00:31:18.905Z\",\"uuid\":\"aab4501f-e26b-4f70-8658-0202297fed90\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"f23f9109-6815-41aa-a287-e66a3615ca83\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"a97d7bdc-76ad-4774-b13f-b81bdd064352\",\"version\":\"2.1.62\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/improve-agent-integration-skill\",\"slug\":\"vast-purring-aurora\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_015BFG28f8ePaSC5x2RXFisa\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1â†’# Write-Tests Command\\n     2â†’\\n     3â†’Create the E2E agent runner only â€” no unit tests, no new test scenarios. The runner registers the agent with the E2E framework so existing `ForEachAgent` tests can exercise it. Uses the implementation one-pager (`AGENT.md`) and the existing E2E test infrastructure.\\n     4â†’\\n     5â†’## Prerequisites\\n     6â†’\\n     7â†’- The research command's one-pager at `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/AGENT.md`\\n     8â†’- If no one-pager exists, ask the user for: binary name, prompt CLI flags, interactive mode support, and hook event names\\n     9â†’\\n    10â†’## Procedure\\n    11â†’\\n    12â†’### Step 1: Read E2E Test Infrastructure\\n    13â†’\\n    14â†’Read these files to understand the existing test patterns.\\n    15â†’\\n    16â†’**Most critical:** Focus on items 3 (`agent.go` â€” the interface you must implement) and read one existing agent implementation (e.g., `e2e/agents/claude.go`) as a reference. Skim the rest for context.\\n    17â†’\\n    18â†’1. `e2e/tests/main_test.go` â€” `TestMain` builds the CLI binary (via `entire.BinPath()`), runs preflight checks for required binaries (git, tmux, agent CLIs), sets up artifact directories, and configures env\\n    19â†’2. `e2e/testutil/repo.go` â€” `RepoState` struct (holds agent, dir, artifact dir, head/checkpoint refs), `SetupRepo` (creates temp git repo, runs `entire enable`, patches settings), `ForEachAgent` (runs a test per registered agent with repo setup, concurrency gating, and timeout scaling)\\n    20â†’3. `e2e/agents/agent.go` â€” `Agent` interface (`Name`, `Binary`, `EntireAgent`, `PromptPattern`, `TimeoutMultiplier`, `RunPrompt`, `StartSession`, `Bootstrap`, `IsTransientError`), `Register()` for agent self-registration in `init()`, `RegisterGate()` for concurrency limits, `AcquireSlot`/`ReleaseSlot` for gating\\n    21â†’4. `e2e/agents/tmux.go` â€” `TmuxSession` for interactive PTY-based tests: `NewTmuxSession`, `Send`, `SendKeys`, `WaitFor` (with settle-time logic), `Capture`, `Close`\\n    22â†’5. `e2e/testutil/assertions.go` â€” Rich assertion helpers: `AssertFileExists`, `WaitForFileExists`, `AssertNewCommits`, `WaitForCheckpoint`, `AssertCheckpointAdvanced`, `AssertHasCheckpointTrailer`, `AssertCheckpointExists`, `AssertCommitLinkedToCheckpoint`, `AssertCheckpointMetadataComplete`, `ValidateCheckpointDeep`, and many more\\n    23â†’6. `e2e/testutil/metadata.go` â€” `CheckpointMetadata`, `SessionMetadata`, `TokenUsage`, `Attribution`, `SessionRef` types; `CheckpointPath()` helper for sharded directory layout\\n    24â†’7. `e2e/entire/entire.go` â€” CLI wrapper: `BinPath()` (builds from source or uses `E2E_ENTIRE_BIN`), `Enable`, `Disable`, `RewindList`, `Rewind`, `RewindLogsOnly`, `Explain`, `ExplainGenerate`, `ExplainCommit`, `Resume`\\n    25â†’8. `e2e/testutil/artifacts.go` â€” Automatic artifact capture via `t.Cleanup`: `CaptureArtifacts` saves git-log, git-tree, checkpoint metadata, entire logs, and tmux pane content\\n    26â†’\\n    27â†’### Step 2: Read Existing E2E Test Scenarios\\n    28â†’\\n    29â†’Run `Glob(\\\"e2e/tests/*_test.go\\\")` to find all existing test files. Read a few to understand the patterns:\\n    30â†’- How tests use `testutil.ForEachAgent` with a timeout and callback `func(t, s, ctx)`\\n    31â†’- How prompts are written inline (no separate prompt template file)\\n    32â†’- How `s.RunPrompt`, `s.Git`, `s.StartSession`, `s.WaitFor`, `s.Send` are used\\n    33â†’- How assertions validate checkpoints, rewind, metadata, etc.\\n    34â†’\\n    35â†’### Step 3: Read Checkpoint Scenarios Doc\\n    36â†’\\n    37â†’Read `docs/architecture/checkpoint-scenarios.md` for the state machine and scenarios the tests should cover.\\n    38â†’\\n    39â†’### Step 4: Create Agent Implementation\\n    40â†’\\n    41â†’Read `cmd/entire/cli/agent/$AGENT_PACKAGE/AGENT.md` (the one-pager from the research phase) for all agent-specific information:\\n    42â†’- Binary name â†’ \\\"Binary\\\" section\\n    43â†’- Prompt flags â†’ \\\"CLI Flags\\\" section\\n    44â†’- Interactive mode â†’ \\\"CLI Flags\\\" section\\n    45â†’- Transient error patterns â†’ \\\"Gaps & Limitations\\\" section (use defaults if not listed)\\n    46â†’- Bootstrap setup â†’ \\\"Config Preservation\\\" section\\n    47â†’\\n    48â†’**If something is missing from the one-pager**, you may search external docs â€” but update `AGENT.md` with anything new you discover.\\n    49â†’\\n    50â†’Add a new `Agent` implementation in `e2e/agents/${agent_slug}.go`:\\n    51â†’\\n    52â†’**Pattern to follow** (based on existing implementations like `claude.go`, `gemini.go`, `opencode.go`):\\n    53â†’\\n    54â†’```go\\n    55â†’package agents\\n    56â†’\\n    57â†’import (\\n    58â†’\\t\\\"context\\\"\\n    59â†’\\t\\\"errors\\\"\\n    60â†’\\t\\\"fmt\\\"\\n    61â†’\\t\\\"os\\\"\\n    62â†’\\t\\\"os/exec\\\"\\n    63â†’\\t\\\"strings\\\"\\n    64â†’\\t\\\"syscall\\\"\\n    65â†’\\t\\\"time\\\"\\n    66â†’)\\n    67â†’\\n    68â†’func init() {\\n    69â†’\\tif env := os.Getenv(\\\"E2E_AGENT\\\"); env != \\\"\\\" && env != \\\"${agent-slug}\\\" {\\n    70â†’\\t\\treturn\\n    71â†’\\t}\\n    72â†’\\tRegister(&${AgentName}{})\\n    73â†’\\t// Optional: limit concurrency for rate-limited agents\\n    74â†’\\t// RegisterGate(\\\"${agent-slug}\\\", 1)\\n    75â†’}\\n    76â†’\\n    77â†’type ${AgentName} struct{}\\n    78â†’\\n    79â†’func (a *${AgentName}) Name() string               { return \\\"${agent-slug}\\\" }\\n    80â†’func (a *${AgentName}) Binary() string             { return \\\"${binary-name}\\\" }\\n    81â†’func (a *${AgentName}) EntireAgent() string        { return \\\"${entire-agent-name}\\\" }\\n    82â†’func (a *${AgentName}) PromptPattern() string      { return `${prompt-regex}` }\\n    83â†’func (a *${AgentName}) TimeoutMultiplier() float64 { return 1.0 }\\n    84â†’\\n    85â†’func (a *${AgentName}) Bootstrap() error {\\n    86â†’\\t// CI-specific setup: auth config, API key injection, warmup, etc.\\n    87â†’\\t// Must be idempotent. Called once before any tests run.\\n    88â†’\\treturn nil\\n    89â†’}\\n    90â†’\\n    91â†’func (a *${AgentName}) IsTransientError(out Output, err error) bool {\\n    92â†’\\tif err == nil {\\n    93â†’\\t\\treturn false\\n    94â†’\\t}\\n    95â†’\\tcombined := out.Stdout + out.Stderr\\n    96â†’\\tfor _, p := range []string{\\\"overloaded\\\", \\\"rate limit\\\", \\\"503\\\", \\\"529\\\"} {\\n    97â†’\\t\\tif strings.Contains(combined, p) {\\n    98â†’\\t\\t\\treturn true\\n    99â†’\\t\\t}\\n   100â†’\\t}\\n   101â†’\\treturn false\\n   102â†’}\\n   103â†’\\n   104â†’func (a *${AgentName}) RunPrompt(ctx context.Context, dir string, prompt string, opts ...Option) (Output, error) {\\n   105â†’\\tcfg := &runConfig{}\\n   106â†’\\tfor _, o := range opts {\\n   107â†’\\t\\to(cfg)\\n   108â†’\\t}\\n   109â†’\\n   110â†’\\targs := []string{/* agent CLI flags for non-interactive prompt execution */}\\n   111â†’\\tcmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, a.Binary(), args...)\\n   112â†’\\tcmd.Dir = dir\\n   113â†’\\tcmd.Env = append(os.Environ(), \\\"ENTIRE_TEST_TTY=0\\\")\\n   114â†’\\tcmd.SysProcAttr = &syscall.SysProcAttr{Setpgid: true}\\n   115â†’\\tcmd.Cancel = func() error {\\n   116â†’\\t\\treturn syscall.Kill(-cmd.Process.Pid, syscall.SIGKILL)\\n   117â†’\\t}\\n   118â†’\\n   119â†’\\tvar stdout, stderr strings.Builder\\n   120â†’\\tcmd.Stdout = &stdout\\n   121â†’\\tcmd.Stderr = &stderr\\n   122â†’\\n   123â†’\\terr := cmd.Run()\\n   124â†’\\texitCode := 0\\n   125â†’\\tif err != nil {\\n   126â†’\\t\\texitErr := &exec.ExitError{}\\n   127â†’\\t\\tif errors.As(err, &exitErr) {\\n   128â†’\\t\\t\\texitCode = exitErr.ExitCode()\\n   129â†’\\t\\t} else {\\n   130â†’\\t\\t\\texitCode = -1\\n   131â†’\\t\\t}\\n   132â†’\\t}\\n   133â†’\\n   134â†’\\treturn Output{\\n   135â†’\\t\\tCommand:  a.Binary() + \\\" \\\" + strings.Join(args, \\\" \\\"),\\n   136â†’\\t\\tStdout:   stdout.String(),\\n   137â†’\\t\\tStderr:   stderr.String(),\\n   138â†’\\t\\tExitCode: exitCode,\\n   139â†’\\t}, err\\n   140â†’}\\n   141â†’\\n   142â†’func (a *${AgentName}) StartSession(ctx context.Context, dir string) (Session, error) {\\n   143â†’\\t// Use NewTmuxSession for interactive PTY support.\\n   144â†’\\t// Return nil if agent doesn't support interactive mode.\\n   145â†’\\tname := fmt.Sprintf(\\\"${agent-slug}-test-%d\\\", time.Now().UnixNano())\\n   146â†’\\ts, err := NewTmuxSession(name, dir, nil, a.Binary(), /* interactive args */)\\n   147â†’\\tif err != nil {\\n   148â†’\\t\\treturn nil, err\\n   149â†’\\t}\\n   150â†’\\treturn s, nil\\n   151â†’}\\n   152â†’```\\n   153â†’\\n   154â†’Key implementation details:\\n   155â†’- Self-register in `init()` with `Register()`, gated by `E2E_AGENT` env var\\n   156â†’- Use `RegisterGate(\\\"name\\\", N)` if the agent's API has strict rate limits (e.g., Gemini uses gate of 1)\\n   157â†’- `Bootstrap()` handles CI-specific one-time setup (auth config, API key injection)\\n   158â†’- `IsTransientError()` identifies retryable API failures â€” `RepoState.RunPrompt` retries once on transient errors\\n   159â†’- `RunPrompt()` uses `exec.CommandContext` with `Setpgid: true` and process-group kill for clean cancellation\\n   160â†’- `StartSession()` uses `NewTmuxSession` for interactive PTY tests; return `nil` if interactive mode isn't supported\\n   161â†’- Use `AGENT.md` (the one-pager) for CLI flags, prompt passing mechanism, and env vars\\n   162â†’\\n   163â†’### Step 5: Update SetupRepo (if needed)\\n   164â†’\\n   165â†’Check if `testutil.SetupRepo` in `e2e/testutil/repo.go` needs agent-specific configuration. Look for the existing `if agent.Name() == \\\"opencode\\\"` block as an example:\\n   166â†’\\n   167â†’- Agent-specific config files that must exist before `entire enable`\\n   168â†’- Permission or auth config files\\n   169â†’- Environment variables needed for hook testing\\n   170â†’\\n   171â†’If no special setup is needed, skip this step.\\n   172â†’\\n   173â†’### Step 6: Verify\\n   174â†’\\n   175â†’After writing the runner code:\\n   176â†’\\n   177â†’1. **Lint check**: `mise run lint` â€” ensure no lint errors\\n   178â†’2. **Compile check**: `go test -c -tags=e2e ./e2e/tests` â€” compile-only with the build tag to verify the runner compiles and registers\\n   179â†’3. **Verify registration**: The runner's `init()` calls `Register()` and will be picked up by `ForEachAgent` in existing tests\\n   180â†’4. **Add mise task**: Remind the user to add a `test:e2e:${agent_slug}` task in `mise.toml` and update CI workflows\\n   181â†’5. **Next step**: The implement phase will run E2E tests against this runner â€” that's where failures are diagnosed and fixed\\n   182â†’\\n   183â†’### Step 7: Commit\\n   184â†’\\n   185â†’Use `/commit` to commit all files.\\n   186â†’\\n   187â†’## Key Conventions\\n   188â†’\\n   189â†’- **Build tag**: All E2E test files must have `//go:build e2e` as the first line\\n   190â†’- **Package**: `package tests` for test files in `e2e/tests/`; `package agents` for agent implementations in `e2e/agents/`\\n   191â†’- **Parallel**: `ForEachAgent` handles parallelism â€” do not call `t.Parallel()` inside the callback\\n   192â†’- **Repo setup**: `ForEachAgent` calls `SetupRepo` automatically â€” do not call it manually\\n   193â†’- **Prompts**: Write prompts inline in the test. Include \\\"Do not ask for confirmation\\\" to prevent agent stalling\\n   194â†’- **Assertions**: Use helpers from `e2e/testutil/assertions.go` â€” see `AssertFileExists`, `WaitForCheckpoint`, `AssertCommitLinkedToCheckpoint`, `ValidateCheckpointDeep`, etc.\\n   195â†’- **CLI operations**: Use the `e2e/entire` package (`entire.Enable`, `entire.RewindList`, `entire.Rewind`, etc.) â€” never call the binary via raw `exec.Command`\\n   196â†’- **No hardcoded paths**: Use `s.Dir` for repo paths, `s.ArtifactDir` for artifacts\\n   197â†’- **Console logging**: All operations through `s.RunPrompt`, `s.Git`, `s.Send`, `s.WaitFor` are automatically logged to `console.log`\\n   198â†’- **Transient errors**: `s.RunPrompt` auto-retries once on transient API errors via `IsTransientError`\\n   199â†’- **Interactive tests**: Use `s.StartSession`, `s.Send`, `s.WaitFor` â€” tmux pane is auto-captured in artifacts\\n   200â†’- **Run commands**: `mise run test:e2e --agent ${slug} TestName` â€” see `e2e/README.md` for all options\\n   201â†’- **E2E tests are run during the implement phase**: This phase only creates the runner. The implement phase runs E2E tests at each tier to drive development.\\n   202â†’- **Debu